Tough question!  I remember, when I was a kid, my dad telling me that religion and politics were better kept to oneself.  I guess many of us were given those same words of wisdom.<br><br>
Many of us lost our innocence in Vietnam and the rest of the sixties and seventies for that matter.  I no longer consider myself a religious person.  Nine years of  parochial school as a kid was more than enough for me to let go of the quest for for spiritual unity.  I have three siblings who are still active in their beliefs.  I'm the black sheep of the family in that regard.  My mom still prays for me.<br><br>
I read a lot of books in the seventies (philosophical and religious) and came out with a thought that I would live my life on earth to the best of my abilities without regard to an afterlife or thoughts of rewards and punishments.<br><br>
Vietnam (as well as some of the rest of life) stripped away a lot of my &quot;illusions,&quot; and I don't choose to return to the old values of my childhood, or new age ideas for that matter.  <br><br>
A good friend once told me not to knock denial if you haven't tried it.  I guess you could take that statement a lot of ways.<br><br>
I find a lot of joy in life in good conversations and partaking in and observing &quot;good deeds.&quot;  I consider that my personal reward and &quot;salvation.&quot;<br><br>
Paul
